The Italian Navy bought a 58 flying boats, the Spanish Navy, 20 specimens with a Hispano-Suiza engine with 300 HP. In France, the machine in the license, was built under the CAMS C-13 and distributed. The Swedish Navy received three p. 13.A civilian Version was marketed under the name of SIAI S. 13.
Technologythe S. 13 was a single-engine biplane fighter reconnaissance flying boat with a crew of two. The Pilot and observer sat side by side in the open Cockpit, and were protected only by a windshield. The canoe-shaped hull consisted of three layers of wood. The wings were covered, as in the previous machines SIAI S. 8 to SIAI S. 12, with linen, and with spars and steel wires attached to the fuselage. The S. 13 was powered by a Isotta Fraschini V6 engine with 250 horsepower and a two-blade propeller. The armament consisted of a 7.7 mm machine gun.
